{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Scientists are arguing about the extent to which it is ethical to pay participants, and whether results of trials that do so can be trusted.", "abstract": "Failure of large-scale National Institutes of Health clinical trial aimed at preventing spread of HIV in Africa has led scientific community to reexamine how such trials should be conducted in poor countries; results show high percentage of women falsely claiming they took medication; main concerns are whether it is ethical to pay clinical trial participants, and whether results are scientifically trustworthy.", "section_name": "Health", "print_page": "12", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"lastname": "McNEIL", "qualifier": "Jr", "rank": 1, "firstname": "Donald", "role": "reported", "organization": "", "middlename": "G."}], "original": "By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/05/health/failed-trial-in-africa-raises-questions-about-how-to-test-hiv-drugs.html", "lead_paragraph": "Scientists are arguing about the extent to which it is ethical to pay participants, and whether results of trials that do so can be trusted.", "headline": {"main": "A Failed Trial in Africa Raises Questions About How to Test H.I.V. Drugs", "print_headline": "A Failed Trial in Africa Raises Questions About How to Test H.I.V. Drugs"}, "_id": "54d2967638f0d81f788a1e42", "word_count": "1170", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/02/05/science/05hiv/05hiv-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/02/05/science/05hiv/05hiv-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 411, "url": "images/2015/02/05/science/05hiv/05hiv-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2015/02/05/science/05hiv/05hiv-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "411"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2015/02/05/science/05hiv/05